  "prompt": "In simple words, how do the air brakes on trucks work?",
  "response": "Air brakes on trucks work using compressed air to control the braking system. Here\u2019s a simple breakdown:\n\n1. **Air Compressor**: A pump on the engine compresses air and stores it in air tanks (reservoirs).\n\n2. **Air Tanks**: The compressed air is stored in these tanks until it\u2019s needed for braking.\n\n3. **Brake Pedal**: When the driver presses the brake pedal, it opens a valve that releases the compressed air.\n\n4. **Air Lines**: The compressed air travels through air lines to the brake chambers near the wheels.\n\n5. **Brake Chambers**: The air pushes a piston or diaphragm inside the brake chamber, which then moves a push rod.\n\n6. **Brake Mechanism**: The push rod applies force to the brake shoes or pads, pressing them against the brake drum or rotor to slow or stop the wheels.\n\n7. **Release**: When the driver releases the brake pedal, the air is vented out, releasing the brake pressure and allowing the wheels to turn freely again.\n\nAir brakes are reliable and powerful, making them ideal for heavy vehicles like trucks. They also have built-in safety features, like spring brakes that automatically engage if the air pressure gets too low, helping to stop the truck safely.",
